---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
	title="Build a Node"
	description="Learn how to build a Madison Mesh node — from choosing hardware and enclosures to solar power and secure mounting."
>
	<div class="container">
		<section class="section" style="padding-top: 2rem;">
			<h1>Build a Node</h1>
			<p>
				A "node" is just a LoRa radio with the right firmware, a good antenna, and a power source. You can
				have a basic indoor node running in under an hour, or build a weatherproof solar-powered outdoor
				node that runs for years with no maintenance.
			</p>
			<p>This page covers common builds from simplest to most capable. Start wherever makes sense for you.</p>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Build types -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Which Type of Node?</h2>

			<div class="card-grid">
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🏠</span>
					<h3>Indoor / Window Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						The simplest possible node. A LoRa radio plugged into a USB charger, placed in an
						upper-floor window with the stock or a short external antenna.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $35–$55 &bull; <strong>Setup time:</strong> 30–60 min &bull; <strong
							>Range:</strong
						> 0.5–3 mi
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🔌</span>
					<h3>Outdoor / Wired Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						Radio in a weatherproof enclosure mounted outside, powered via a USB or PoE cable from
						indoors. Best range improvement for the cost.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $60–$120 &bull; <strong>Setup time:</strong> 2–4 hrs &bull; <strong
							>Range:</strong
						> 2–10+ mi
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">☀️</span>
					<h3>Solar / Off-Grid Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						A fully self-contained node with solar panel, LiPo battery, and MPPT charge controller.
						Can be placed anywhere with sunlight — no power outlet needed.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $80–$200 &bull; <strong>Setup time:</strong> 4–8 hrs &bull; <strong
							>Range:</strong
						> 2–20+ mi
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Parts list -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>What You Need</h2>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The Radio</h3>
			<p>Any LoRa radio running MeshCore or Meshtastic firmware will work. Popular options:</p>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<strong>Heltec Wireless Tracker</strong> — compact, built-in display &amp; GPS, good all-around pick
					($35–$45)
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Heltec V3</strong> — very popular, built-in OLED display, widely supported ($25–$35)
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>LilyGo T-Beam Supreme</strong> — GPS built-in, large battery, best for mobile use ($45–$65)
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>RAK WisBlock 4631</strong> — modular, designed for outdoor enclosure builds ($40–$60)
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Seeed SenseCAP T1000-E</strong> — credit-card sized, very rugged, minimal setup ($50–$60)
				</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="text-muted">
				All of the above use SX1262 LoRa chips and support the US 915 MHz band. Avoid older SX1276-based
				boards (Heltec V1/V2, TTGO LoRa32 v1) for new builds — they have worse sensitivity.
			</p>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Antenna</h3>
			<p>
				See the <a href="/coverage">Coverage &amp; Antennas</a> page for a full breakdown. For most fixed nodes,
				any <strong>3–5 dBi 915 MHz fiberglass omni antenna</strong> is a good choice ($10–$25 on Amazon). Make
				sure the connector matches your radio (usually RP-SMA or SMA female).
			</p>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Enclosure (outdoor builds)</h3>
			<p>For outdoor use your radio must be protected from moisture. Common options:</p>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<strong>IP67 ABS junction box</strong> — cheap and widely available, comes in sizes to fit most boards.
					Use cable glands for wire entry.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Hammond 1550Z series</strong> — quality aluminum enclosure, great for solar builds with DIN
					rail inside.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>3D-printed enclosures</strong> — community members share designs. PETG or ASA plastic handles
					outdoor UV and temperature. Ask on Discord.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Commercial outdoor IoT cases</strong> — RAK makes enclosures designed specifically for their
					WisBlock modules.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Power</h3>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<strong>Indoor / wired:</strong> Any 5V USB power adapter. A small power bank can add hours of backup.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Solar:</strong> A 6–10W solar panel, a 2000–5000 mAh LiPo battery, and a small MPPT solar
					charge controller (e.g., CN3791-based modules). Many radios include a built-in LiPo connector — pair
					with an 18650 cell for great runtime.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<div
				class="card"
				style="margin-top: 1.5rem; background-color: oklch(22% 0.06 232.69); border-color: var(--clr-primary-darker);"
			>
				<h3 style="color: var(--clr-primary);">💬 Community tip</h3>
				<p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
					The Madison Mesh Discord has a <strong>#hardware</strong> channel where members share their specific
					builds, enclosure choices, and what's working well in Wisconsin's climate. If you're unsure what
					to buy, ask there first!
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Step by step build -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Building an Outdoor Wired Node (Step by Step)</h2>
			<p>
				This is the build we recommend for most community members who want to make a real impact on network
				coverage. It's more capable than an indoor node but doesn't require solar.
			</p>

			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">1</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Flash firmware</h3>
						<p>
							Before boxing everything up, flash and configure your radio indoors first. See the
							<a href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a> guide for firmware flashing instructions.
							Test that it connects to the Madison Mesh channel and can see other nodes.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">2</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Prepare the enclosure</h3>
						<p>
							Drill or cut holes for the antenna connector and USB cable entry. Use cable glands to
							seal around any wire penetrations. Silicone sealant around edges can add extra
							weather protection. Avoid drilling on the top of the box — drill on the bottom or
							sides so water doesn't collect around entries.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">3</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Mount the radio inside</h3>
						<p>
							Secure the radio inside the box using double-sided foam tape, a 3D-printed bracket,
							or short standoffs. Leave enough slack in the antenna pigtail to close the box
							easily. Add a desiccant packet to absorb any moisture that sneaks in.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">4</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Mount the enclosure and antenna</h3>
						<p>
							Mount the box to a mast, pole, eave, or wall using U-bolts, hose clamps, or stainless
							screws. Mount the antenna with its base at or above the roofline — the higher, the
							better. Keep the antenna coax run as short as possible.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">5</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Run power and test</h3>
						<p>
							Run a USB cable from the node to an indoor USB adapter. Weatherproof any exterior
							cable runs with UV-resistant zip ties and conduit if needed. Power on, confirm
							connection to other nodes, and you're live!
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<section class="section">
			<h2>Node configuration tips</h2>
			<p>
				Once your node is online, set it to the correct <strong>role</strong> for its purpose:
			</p>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li><strong>Client</strong> — for handheld or personal nodes you actively use to send messages.</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Router</strong> — for fixed nodes that relay traffic. Uses minimal battery and prioritizes
					routing. Best for rooftop nodes.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Router/Client</strong> — for a fixed node where you also want to send messages occasionally.
				</li>
			</ul>
			<p>
				For MeshCore, similar roles exist under different names — ask in the Discord for current guidance on
				the Madison Mesh configuration.
			</p>
			<a
				href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noopener noreferrer"
				class="btn btn-primary"
			>
				Ask questions on Discord &rarr;
			</a>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
